il 2020\n|0\n|99<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/corona-virus/kktc-de-bugun-yeni-vaka-yok-h86943.html|title=KKTC'de bug\u00fcn yeni vaka yok!|website=K\u0131br\u0131s Gazetesi}}</ref>\n|-\n|12 April 2020\n|0\n|99\n|-\n|13 April 2020\n|1\n|100\n|-\n|14 April 2020\n|0\n|100\n|-\n|15 April 2020\n|2\n|102\n|-\n|}\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=550\n|colors=#F46D43,#A50026\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=10 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1=1, 2, 5, 5, 6, 7, 20, 20, 33, 33, 35, 38, 40, 40, 42, 47, 61, 61, 61, 69, 70, 77, 81, 88, 88, 91, 92, 94, 95, 96, 99, 99\n|y1Title=Total confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid= \n}}\n\n==Reaction==\n\nOn 11 March 2020, Turkish Cypriot Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister [[Kudret \u00d6zersay]] said in a tweet that flights from [[Germany]], [[France]] and [[Italy]] to Northern Cyprus would be suspended until 1 April 2020.<ref name=\"Case_2\" />\n\nOn 12 March 2020, the [[Turkish republic of northern Cyprus]] government shut schools and banned mass gatherings as precautionary measures to prevent the spread of the coronavirus, which the [[World Health Organisation]] declared a pandemic.<ref name=\"Case_2\" />\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cyprus]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Northern Cyprus|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cyprus|Northern Cyprus]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox outbreak\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]]\n| first_case = [[Nicosia]]\n| arrival_date = 10 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=10|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| first_outbreak = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases = 44<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/kibris/kktcde-bir-kiside-daha-koronavirus-vakasi-h85865.html|title=KKTC'de bir ki\u015fide daha Koronavir\u00fcs vakas\u0131!|website=kibrisgazetesi.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths = 3<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tr.euronews.com/2020/03/28/kktc-de-koronavirus-nedeniyle-ilk-olum|title=KKTC'de koronavir\u00fcs nedeniyle ilk \u00f6l\u00fcm|date=28 March 2020|website=euronews|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/dunya/kktcde-korona-virusten-2-olum-41483719|title=KKTC'de Korona vir\u00fcsten 2. \u00f6l\u00fcm|website=www.hurriyet.com.tr|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 100\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Northern Cyprus]], officially the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus (the Turkish-Cypriot-controlled ''[[de facto]]'' state comprising the north of the island), in March 2020.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 10 March 2020, Health Minister [[Ali Pilli]] announced the Northern Cyprus's first case of [[COVID-19]], a 65-year-old tourist from [[Germany]].<ref name=\"First\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/03/10/german-tourist-tests-positive-for-virus-in-northern-cyprus-.html |title=German tourist tests positive for virus in Northern Cyprus |date=13 March 2020 |via=athejakartapost}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, the country's second case was confirmed, being the spouse of the German tourist who became the first person diagnosed with COVID-19.<ref name=\"Case_2\">{{Cite web |url=https://ahvalnews.com/coronavirus/second-coronavirus-case-northern-cyprus |title=Second coronavirus case in northern Cyprus |date=13 March 2020 |via=aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus (TRNC) announced that five people have been tested positive for the coronavirus, up from two.<ref name=\"Case_5\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/health/northern-cyprus-confirms-total-of-5-coronavirus-cases/1764711 |title=Northern Cyprus confirms total of 5 coronavirus cases |date=13 March 2020 |via=aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the [[2020 Northern Cypriot presidential election]] was delayed for 6 months due to the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnturk.com/turkiye/kktcde-cumhurbaskanligi-secimleri-6-ay-erteleniyor|title=KKTC'de Cumhurba\u015fkanl\u0131\u011f\u0131 se\u00e7imleri 6 ay erteleniyor|website=CNN T\u00fcrk|language=tr|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, over 840 [[Germans|German]] national tourists were sent back to [[Germany]] after being quarantined for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/avrupa/kktcde-karantinadaki-almanlar-ulkelerine-donuyor-41476774|title=KKTC'de karantinadaki Almanlar \u00fclkelerine d\u00f6n\u00fcyor|first=Sefa KARAHASAN|last=DHA|website=www.hurriyet.com.tr|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, the first person died from COVID-19.\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nNorth Cyprus announced partial curfew until 10 April. The exception is just for using markets and other mandatory needs. Moreover, fully curfew is under action within the 9pm to 6am until 10 April.\n\n15 villages within the \u0130skele/Karpaz district is under application of the fully curfew due to high number of cases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-cyprus-declares-curfew-153448 |title=Turkish Cyprus declares curfew |website=Hurriyet Daily News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTurkish Cypriot authorities banned movement between districts, meaning no one will be allowed to travel from one district to another.\n\nThree students of 800 who came from UK were under self isolated quarantine for 14 days, have tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/corona-virus/kktc-de-koronavirus-vaka-sayisi-91-oldu-h86514.html|title=KKTC'de Koronavir\u00fcs vaka say\u0131s\u0131 91 oldu|website=kibrisgazetesi.com}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Day !! New cases !! Cumulative cases\n|-\n| {{dts|10 March 2020}} || 1 || 1\n|-\n| {{dts|12 March 2020}} || 1 || 2\n|-\n| {{dts|13 March 2020}} || 3 || 5\n|-\n| {{dts|14 March 2020}} || 0 || 5\n|-\n| {{dts|15 March 2020}} || 1 || 6\n|-\n| {{dts|16 March 2020}}|| 1 || 7\n|-\n| {{dts|17 March 2020}} || 13 || 20\n|-\n| {{dts|18 March 2020}} || 0 ||  20\n|-\n| {{dts|19 March 2020}} || 13 || 33<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/koronavirus/kktcde-kovid-19-vaka-sayisi-33e-yukseldi/1772461|title=KKTC'de Kovid-19 vaka say\u0131s\u0131 33'e y\u00fckseldi|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|20 March 2020}} || 0 || 33\n|-\n| {{dts|21 March 2020}} || 2 || 35<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gundemkibris.com/kibris/son-dakika-1-yeni-vaka-daha-goruldu-h292140.html|title=SON DAK\u0130KA! 1 yeni vaka daha g\u00f6r\u00fcld\u00fc|first=G\u00fcndem K\u0131br\u0131s|last=Gazetesi|website=www.gundemkibris.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|22 March 2020}} || 3 || 38<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olay.com.tr/kktcde-corona-virus-vaka-sayisi-38e-yukseldi-545542|title=KKTC'de corona vir\u00fcs vaka say\u0131s\u0131 38'e y\u00fckseldi - Olay Gazetesi Bursa|date=22 March 2020|website=Olay|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|23 March 2020}} || 2 || 40<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeturk.com/kktc-de-korona-virusu-vaka-sayisi-40-a-yukseldi/haber-1403788|title=KKTC'de korona vir\u00fcs\u00fc vaka say\u0131s\u0131 40'a y\u00fckseldi|website=Timeturk.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|24 March 2020}} || 0 || 40\n|-\n| {{dts|25 March 2020}} || 2 || 42<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haberturk.com/kktc-de-koronavirus-vaka-sayisi-42-ye-yukseldi-2624017|title=2 ki\u015fide daha koronavir\u00fcs testi pozitif \u00e7\u0131kt\u0131|website=www.haberturk.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|26 March 2020}} || 5 || 47<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/kibris/kktcdeki-koronavirus-vaka-sayisi-47ye-yukseldi-h85775.html|title=KKTC'deki Koronavir\u00fcs vaka say\u0131s\u0131 47'ye y\u00fckseldi|website=kibrisgazetesi.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|27 March 2020}} || 14 || 61<ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/corona-virus/kktcde-koronavirus-vakalarinda-son-durum-h85894.html|title=KKTC'de koronavir\u00fcs vakalar\u0131nda son durum|website=kibrisgazetesi.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|30 March 2020}} || 8 || 69<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/kibris/kktc-de-koronavirus-salginina-karsi-geceleri-tam-sokaga-cikma-h86106.html|title=KKTC'de Koronavir\u00fcs salg\u0131n\u0131na kar\u015f\u0131 geceleri tam soka\u011fa \u00e7\u0131kma yasa\u011f\u0131|website=www.kibrisgazetesi.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|31 March 2020}} || 1 || 70<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/corona-virus/kktcde-1-yeni-koronavirus-vakasi-daha-h86166.html|title=KKTC'de 1 yeni Koronavir\u00fcs vakas\u0131 daha|website=kibrisgazetesi.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1 April 2020}} || 7 || 77<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/kibris/kktcde-7-yeni-koronavirus-vakasi-daha-vaka-sayisi-77-ye-h86241.html|title=KKTC'de 7 yeni Koronavir\u00fcs vakas\u0131 daha! Vaka say\u0131s\u0131 77'ye \u00e7\u0131kt\u0131|website=www.kibrisgazetesi.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|2 April 2020}} || 4 || 81\n|-\n| {{dts|3 April 2020}} || 7 || 88<ref>{{cite news |title=29 ki\u015fi ise tedavi edilerek taburcu oldu |url=https://www.haberturk.com/kktcde-koronavirus-vakalari-88e-yukseldi-2634959 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=www.haberturk.com |language=tr}}</ref>\n|-\n| 4 April 2020 || 0 || 88\n|-\n|5 April 2020\n|3\n|91\n|-\n|6 April 2020\n|1\n|92\n|-\n|7 April 2020\n|2\n|94<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/corona-virus/kktcde-2-yeni-koronavirus-vakasi-h86668.html|title=KKTC'de 2 yeni koronavir\u00fcs vakas\u0131!|website=kibrisgazetesi.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|8 April 2020\n|1\n|95\n|-\n|9 April 2020\n|1\n|96<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrispostasi.com/c77-SAGLIK_KISISEL_BAKIM/n319126-lefkede-bir-pozitif-vaka|title=Lefke'de bir pozitif vaka!|website=KIBRIS POSTASI}}</ref>\n|-\n|10 April 2020\n|3\n|99 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gundemkibris.com/kibris/son-dakika-ali-pilli-3-yeni-pozitif-vaka-daha-goruldu-h293314.html|title=Ali Pilli: \"3 yeni pozitif vaka daha g\u00f6r\u00fcld\u00fc\"|website=Gundem Kibris}}</ref>\n|-\n|11 April 2020\n|0\n|99<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kibrisgazetesi.com/corona-virus/kktc-de-bugun-yeni-vaka-yok-h86943.html|title=KKTC'de bug\u00fcn yeni vaka yok!|website=K\u0131br\u0131s Gazetesi}}</ref>\n|-\n|12 April 2020\n|0\n|99\n|-\n|13 April 2020\n|1\n|100\n|-\n|14 April 2020\n|0\n|100\n|-\n|}\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=550\n|colors=#F46D43,#A50026\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=10 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1=1, 2, 5, 5, 6, 7, 20, 20, 33, 33, 35, 38, 40, 40, 42, 47, 61, 61, 61, 69, 70, 77, 81, 88, 88, 91, 92, 94, 95, 96, 99, 99\n|y1Title=Total confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid= \n}}\n\n==Reaction==\n\nOn 11 March 2020, Turkish Cypriot Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister [[Kudret \u00d6zersay]] said in a tweet that flights from [[Germany]], [[France]] and [[Italy]] to Northern Cyprus would be suspended until 1 April 2020.<ref name=\"Case_2\" />\n\nOn 12 March 2020, the [[Turkish republic of northern Cyprus]] government shut schools and banned mass gatherings as precautionary measures to prevent the spread of the coronavirus, which the [[World Health Organisation]] declared a pandemic.<ref name=\"Case_2\" />\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cyprus]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Northern Cyprus|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Northern Cyprus]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cyprus|Northern Cyprus]]\n", "name_user": "Highlanderwolf", "label": "safe", "comment": "Daily update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Northern_Cyprus"}
{"title_page": "Ron Reagan", "text_new": "{{for|his father and the 40th President of the United States|Ronald Reagan}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person \n|birthname     = Ronald Prescott Reagan\n|image         = Ron_Reagan.jpg\n|alt           = Ron Reagan in 2008\n|caption       = Ron Reagan in 2008\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1958|05|20}}\n|birth_place   = [[Pits of Hell]], [[Satans cloning chamber]], Hell.\n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|residence     = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.\n|education     = [[Yale University]] (1976)\n|occupation    = Radio show host, writer\n|employer      = [[MSNBC]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Doria Palmieri|1980|2014|end=d.}}<br>{{marriage|Federica Basagni|2018}}\n|parents       = {{plain list|\n* [[Ronald Reagan]]\n* [[Nancy Reagan]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Ronald Prescott Reagan''' (born May 20, 1958) is an American former radio host and political analyst for [[KIRO (AM)|KIRO]] radio and later, [[Air America Media|Air America Radio]], where he hosted his own daily three-hour show. He is a commentator and contributor to programming on the [[MSNBC]] cable news and commentary network. His [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] views contrast with those of his late father, [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]  United States President [[Ronald Reagan]].\n\n==Early life==\nReagan was born and raised in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], the son of Ronald Reagan and his second wife, [[Nancy Davis Reagan]]. The family lived in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] while his father was [[Governor of California|governor]], from 1967 {{nowrap|to 1975.<ref name=erbchprvy>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6NlVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7uADAAAAIBAJ&pg=6597%2C4156380 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |last=Zeboski |first=Walt |title=Reagans cherish privacy despite a very public life |date=November 18, 1971 |page=1C}}</ref>}}   His sister, [[Patti Davis]], is five and a half years older. His elder brother [[Michael Reagan]], adopted as an infant by [[Ronald Reagan]] and his first wife [[Jane Wyman]], is 13 years older. He also had two half-sisters born to Reagan and Wyman, [[Maureen Reagan]] (1941\u20132001) and Christine Reagan, who was born prematurely, on June 26, 1947, and died the same day. At an early age, his father, Ronald Reagan, often joked that they were related to every royal family with the name O'Regan in Europe. [[Burke's Peerage]] provided the Reagans with their family tree, which lacked any direct connection to European royalty.<ref>{{Cite book|title=My father at 100|last=1958-|first=Reagan, Ron|date=2011|publisher=Viking|isbn=9780670022595|location=New York|oclc=646111792}}</ref>\n\nRon Reagan undertook a different philosophical and political path from his father at an early age. At 12, he told his parents that he would not be going to church anymore because he was an [[atheist]].<ref name=\"thehill\">[http://thehill.com/capital-living/20-questions/20867-20-questions-ron-reagan \"20 Questions: Ron Reagan\"], by Betsy Rothstein, ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', September 24, 2008.</ref>\n\nReagan attended and was expelled from [[The Webb Schools|The Webb School of California]]. He commented:\n\n<blockquote>They [the school administration] thought I was a bad influence on the other kids. As I recall, the immediate reason was I went to a dance at a neighboring girl's school in a classmate's car. This was an infraction. They had been looking for an excuse. I didn't get caught at anything.<ref name=\"thehill\"/></blockquote>\n\nReagan dropped out of [[Yale University]] in 1976 after one semester to become a [[ballet]] dancer.<ref name=\"thehill\"/> He joined the [[Joffrey Ballet]] in pursuit of his lifelong dream and participated in the Joffrey II Dancers, a troupe for beginning dancers, where he was mentored by [[Sally Brayley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20079241,00.html|title=What Do You Call the Connection Between the Metropolitan Opera and Ron Reagan's Dance Troupe? Wedded Bliss : People.com|website=www.people.com|access-date=2016-05-08}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' wrote in 1980: \"It is widely known that Ron's parents have not managed to see a single ballet performance of their son, who is clearly very good, having been selected to the Joffrey second company, and is their son nonetheless. Ron talks of his parents with much affection. But these absences are strange and go back a ways.\" Reagan and Nancy went to see Ron perform at the [[Lisner Auditorium]] on Monday, May 18, 1981. The elder Reagan commented in his [[White House]] diary on this day that Ron's performance was reminiscent of [[Fred Astaire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reaganfoundation.org/ronald-reagan/white-house-diaries/diary-entry-05181981/ |title=White House Diaries: Monday, May 18, 1981|accessdate= July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Careers==\nReagan became more politically active after his father left the White House in 1989. In contrast to his father, the younger Reagan's views were unabashedly liberal. In a 2009 ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' interview, Ron said that he did not speak out politically during his father's term because the press \"never cared about my opinions ''as such,'' only as they related to ''him''\", adding that he did not want to create the impression that he and his father were on bad terms because of political differences. In 1991, Reagan hosted ''The Ron Reagan Show'', a syndicated late-night talk show addressing political issues of the day, which was canceled after a brief run since it was unable to compete with the higher ratings of ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]'', ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'', and ''[[Nightline (U.S. news program)|Nightline]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nReagan has worked in recent years as a magazine journalist, and has hosted talk shows on cable TV networks such as the [[Animal Planet]] network. In [[United Kingdom|Britain]], he is best known for having co-presented ''[[Record Breakers]]'' (based on ''[[The Guinness Book of Records]]'') for the [[BBC]]. Reagan presented a report from the United States each week.<ref>[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/571186/index.html Profile], screenonline.org.uk; accessed September 2, 2014.</ref>\n\nHe has served on the board of the [[Creative Coalition]], an organization founded in 1989 by a group that included [[Susan Sarandon]] and [[Christopher Reeve]], to politically mobilize entertainers and artists, generally for [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] rights, and causes such as arts advocacy and public education. From February to December 2005, Reagan co-hosted the talk show ''[[Connected: Coast to Coast]] with [[Monica Crowley]]'' on [[MSNBC]].<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|713985}}</ref>\n\nUntil its demise in 2010, [[Air America Media]] aired ''The Ron Reagan Show.'' The program made its debut on September 8, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reagan Joins Air America as Permanent Weeknight Host|work=Radio Online|date=September 4, 2008|url=http://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/$rol.exe/headline_id=n18357|accessdate=2013-11-27|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122220742/http://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/$rol.exe/headline_id=n18357|archivedate=2009-01-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, he published ''My Father at 100: A Memoir''.<ref name=\"Father at 100\">{{cite book | title=My Father at 100 | author=Ron Reagan |year=2011 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-670-02259-5 |oclc=646111792}}</ref> In interviews promoting the book, Reagan described noticing his father was having certain mental lapses which, in hindsight, caused the younger Reagan to speculate subsequently that his father may have already been in the early stages of [[Alzheimer's disease]] while still in office. This assertion was attacked by critics, including his brother, Michael Reagan. Ron Reagan subsequently clarified that he did not feel the lapses were evidence of \"dementia.\"<ref>''[[The Colbert Report]]'', January 18, 2011</ref>\n\nIn February of 1986, Reagan hosted ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.\n\n==Political activities==\nIn July 2004, Reagan spoke at the [[2004 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] about his support for lifting Bush's restrictions on federally funded [[embryonic stem cell research]], from which he expected a cure or new treatments for [[Alzheimer's disease]], of which his father had recently died. \"There are those who would stand in the way of this remarkable future, who would deny the federal funding so crucial to basic research. A few of these folks, needless to say, are just grinding a political axe and they should be ashamed of themselves,\" Ron Reagan said of the restrictions. \"We can choose between the future and the past, between reason and ignorance, between true compassion and mere ideology.\"<ref name=DNCSpeech>{{cite news|first=|last= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/27/politics/campaign/27TEXT-REAGAN.html|title=Ron Reagan's Speech to the Democratic National Convention|work=[[New York Times]]|date=Jul 27, 2004|accessdate=Sep 13, 2015}}</ref> Reagan's mother Nancy also supported this position.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/3700015.stm ''Nancy Reagan plea on stem cells'']. [[BBC News]]. May 10, 2004.</ref>\n\nIn September 2004, he told the ''[[Sunday Herald]]'' newspaper that the [[George W. Bush]] Administration had \"cheated to get into the White House. It's not something Americans ever want to think about their government. My sense of these people is that they don't have any respect for the public at large. They have a revolutionary mindset. I think they feel that anything they can do to prevail &mdash; lie, cheat, whatever &mdash; is justified by their revolutionary aims\" and that he feared Bush was \"hijacking\" his father's reputation.<ref>Johnston, Jenifer. [http://rense.com/general57/stop.htm ''Reagan Junior Warns Bush: 'Stop Hijacking My Father's Reputation'&#8288;'']. ''[[Sunday Herald]]''. September 26, 2004.</ref>\n\nReagan later wrote the essay \"The Case Against George W. Bush by Ron Reagan\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/cgi-bin/printtool/print.cgi?pages=5&filename=%2Ffeatures%2Farticles%2F2004%2F040729_mfe_reagan.html&x=38&y=16 |title=The Case Against George W. Bush |first=Ron |last=Reagan |work=[[Esquire Magazine|Esquire]] |year=2004 |accessdate=April 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040810032603/http://www.esquire.com/cgi-bin/printtool/print.cgi?pages=5&filename=%2Ffeatures%2Farticles%2F2004%2F040729_mfe_reagan.html&x=38&y=16 |archivedate=August 10, 2004 }}</ref> for ''[[Esquire Magazine|Esquire]]''. He voted for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate [[John Kerry]] in the [[U.S. presidential election, 2004|2004 presidential election]]. Reagan endorsed then-senator [[Barack Obama]] of Illinois for president in the [[U.S. presidential election, 2008|2008 presidential election]].<ref>Reagan, Ron. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ron-reagan/making-it-official-i-endo_b_139932.html ''Making It Official: I Endorse Barack Obama'']. [[The Huffington Post]]. October 31, 2008.</ref> In November 2015, Reagan endorsed [[Vermont]] Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] for the Democratic Party nomination in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Democratic Party primaries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/09/reagan-sons-interview-donald-trump-213149|title=GOP 2016: The Reagan Brothers on Donald Trump and the GOP|work=Politico Magazine|first=Elizabeth F.|last=Ralph|date=September 16, 2015|accessdate=November 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Reagan stated that his father would've opposed [[Donald Trump]], remarking to ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' that his \"father would have been ashamed of this Republican Party\" as well as \"been embarrassed and ashamed that a president of the United States was as incompetent and traitorous as the man occupying the White House now.\"<ref>https://www.thedailybeast.com/ron-reagan-says-his-father-ronald-reagan-would-not-want-republicans-to-vote-for-traitor-trump-in-2020</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRon Reagan lives in [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]].<ref name=\"thehill\"/> He married Doria Palmieri, a [[clinical psychology|clinical psychologist]], in 1980. She died in 2014 from [[neuromuscular disease]]. They had no children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/abcarian/la-me-ra-ron-reagan-endorses-atheism-20140530-column.html|title=Ron Reagan, not afraid to burn in hell, promotes atheism in TV spot|date=2014-05-30|accessdate=2014-06-12}}</ref> He married Federica Basagni in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/ron-reagan-says-his-father-ronald-reagan-would-not-want-republicans-to-vote-for-traitor-trump-in-2020 |title=Ron Reagan Says His Father, Ronald Reagan, Would Not Want Republicans to Vote for 'Traitor' Trump in 2020 |publisher=Thedailybeast.com |date=2020-01-17 |accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nReagan stated, in a 2004 ''[[New York Times]]'' interview, that he did not claim any religion, but that his sympathies were with [[Buddhism]] and his wife was a Buddhist.<ref name=\"SolomonInterview\">{{cite news|first=Deborah|last=Solomon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/27/magazine/27QUESTIONS.html?ex=1205812800&en=2cf65449d478f3c3&ei=5070|title=The Son Also Rises|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 27, 2004|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> In a June 23, 2004, interview on [[CNN]] show ''[[Larry King Live]]'', while discussing reasons why he would not run for political office, Ron Reagan stated \"I'm an [[atheism|atheist]]. ... I can't be elected to anything because polls all say that people won't elect an atheist.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview With Ron Reagan Jr.|work=Larry King Live (transcript)|publisher=CNN.com|date=June 23, 2004|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0406/23/lkl.00.html|accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, he was named to the [[Freedom From Religion Foundation]]'s Honorary Board of distinguished achievers.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://ffrf.org/news/releases/honorary-ffrf-board-announced/ |title= Honorary FFRF Board Announced |accessdate=2008-08-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101217052917/http://ffrf.org/news/releases/honorary-ffrf-board-announced/|archivedate=2010-12-17}}</ref> \nIn May 2014, Reagan appeared in an advertisement for broadcast on [[Comedy Central]] for the Freedom From Religion Foundation in which he declared himself \"an unabashed atheist,\" and one who is not afraid of \"burning\" in [[Hell]].<ref name=FFRF052014>{{cite web|title=First 'atheist ad' on 'Daily Show,' 'Colbert Report' features Ron Reagan|url=http://ffrf.org/news/news-releases/item/20732-first-%E2%80%98atheist-ad%E2%80%99-on-%E2%80%98daily-show%E2%80%99-%E2%80%98colbert-report%E2%80%99-features-ron-reagan|publisher=Freedom From Religion Foundation|date=May 20, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> The ad received renewed attention in October 2019 when it aired on CNN during the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums#Fourth debate (October 15, 2019)|fourth 2020 Democratic Presidential Debate]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A lot of people were Googling 'Ron Reagan' after his atheism ad aired|url=https://www.whas11.com/article/news/nation-world/ron-reagan-atheism-ad/507-90c1b182-e182-4060-9c5c-78433ad0c0cf|date=2019-10-15|accessdate=2019-10-16}}</ref> The ad was also run during the [[CNN]] Democratic debate in January 2020 and March 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|Journalism|Liberalism|Politics|Television|California|Chicago|United States|Religion}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2003/04/14/ron_reagan/ Reagan Blasts Bush (2003 interview)]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/15/us/2004-campaign-political-memo-reaganite-association-his-family-won-t-allow-it.html NYT: Reaganite by Association? His Family Won't Allow It]\n*[http://www.pr.com/article/1122 Ron Reagan] Interview on PR.com\n*{{C-SPAN|Ron Reagan}}\n*{{IMDb name|0713985|Ron Reagan}}\n\n{{Ronald Reagan}}\n{{Nancy Reagan}}\n{{MSNBC personalities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reagan, Ron}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American male ballet dancers]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Children of Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Reagan family|Ron]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Writers from Seattle]]\n[[Category:MSNBC people]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:21st-century atheists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|his father and the 40th President of the United States|Ronald Reagan}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person \n|birthname     = Ronald Prescott Reagan\n|image         = Ron_Reagan.jpg\n|alt           = Ron Reagan in 2008\n|caption       = Ron Reagan in 2008\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1958|05|20}}\n|birth_place   = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|residence     = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.\n|education     = [[Yale University]] (1976)\n|occupation    = Radio show host, writer\n|employer      = [[MSNBC]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Doria Palmieri|1980|2014|end=d.}}<br>{{marriage|Federica Basagni|2018}}\n|parents       = {{plain list|\n* [[Ronald Reagan]]\n* [[Nancy Reagan]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Ronald Prescott Reagan''' (born May 20, 1958) is an American former radio host and political analyst for [[KIRO (AM)|KIRO]] radio and later, [[Air America Media|Air America Radio]], where he hosted his own daily three-hour show. He is a commentator and contributor to programming on the [[MSNBC]] cable news and commentary network. His [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] views contrast with those of his late father, [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]  United States President [[Ronald Reagan]].\n\n==Early life==\nReagan was born and raised in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], the son of Ronald Reagan and his second wife, [[Nancy Davis Reagan]]. The family lived in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] while his father was [[Governor of California|governor]], from 1967 {{nowrap|to 1975.<ref name=erbchprvy>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6NlVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7uADAAAAIBAJ&pg=6597%2C4156380 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |last=Zeboski |first=Walt |title=Reagans cherish privacy despite a very public life |date=November 18, 1971 |page=1C}}</ref>}}   His sister, [[Patti Davis]], is five and a half years older. His elder brother [[Michael Reagan]], adopted as an infant by [[Ronald Reagan]] and his first wife [[Jane Wyman]], is 13 years older. He also had two half-sisters born to Reagan and Wyman, [[Maureen Reagan]] (1941\u20132001) and Christine Reagan, who was born prematurely, on June 26, 1947, and died the same day. At an early age, his father, Ronald Reagan, often joked that they were related to every royal family with the name O'Regan in Europe. [[Burke's Peerage]] provided the Reagans with their family tree, which lacked any direct connection to European royalty.<ref>{{Cite book|title=My father at 100|last=1958-|first=Reagan, Ron|date=2011|publisher=Viking|isbn=9780670022595|location=New York|oclc=646111792}}</ref>\n\nRon Reagan undertook a different philosophical and political path from his father at an early age. At 12, he told his parents that he would not be going to church anymore because he was an [[atheist]].<ref name=\"thehill\">[http://thehill.com/capital-living/20-questions/20867-20-questions-ron-reagan \"20 Questions: Ron Reagan\"], by Betsy Rothstein, ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', September 24, 2008.</ref>\n\nReagan attended and was expelled from [[The Webb Schools|The Webb School of California]]. He commented:\n\n<blockquote>They [the school administration] thought I was a bad influence on the other kids. As I recall, the immediate reason was I went to a dance at a neighboring girl's school in a classmate's car. This was an infraction. They had been looking for an excuse. I didn't get caught at anything.<ref name=\"thehill\"/></blockquote>\n\nReagan dropped out of [[Yale University]] in 1976 after one semester to become a [[ballet]] dancer.<ref name=\"thehill\"/> He joined the [[Joffrey Ballet]] in pursuit of his lifelong dream and participated in the Joffrey II Dancers, a troupe for beginning dancers, where he was mentored by [[Sally Brayley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20079241,00.html|title=What Do You Call the Connection Between the Metropolitan Opera and Ron Reagan's Dance Troupe? Wedded Bliss : People.com|website=www.people.com|access-date=2016-05-08}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' wrote in 1980: \"It is widely known that Ron's parents have not managed to see a single ballet performance of their son, who is clearly very good, having been selected to the Joffrey second company, and is their son nonetheless. Ron talks of his parents with much affection. But these absences are strange and go back a ways.\" Reagan and Nancy went to see Ron perform at the [[Lisner Auditorium]] on Monday, May 18, 1981. The elder Reagan commented in his [[White House]] diary on this day that Ron's performance was reminiscent of [[Fred Astaire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reaganfoundation.org/ronald-reagan/white-house-diaries/diary-entry-05181981/ |title=White House Diaries: Monday, May 18, 1981|accessdate= July 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Careers==\nReagan became more politically active after his father left the White House in 1989. In contrast to his father, the younger Reagan's views were unabashedly liberal. In a 2009 ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' interview, Ron said that he did not speak out politically during his father's term because the press \"never cared about my opinions ''as such,'' only as they related to ''him''\", adding that he did not want to create the impression that he and his father were on bad terms because of political differences. In 1991, Reagan hosted ''The Ron Reagan Show'', a syndicated late-night talk show addressing political issues of the day, which was canceled after a brief run since it was unable to compete with the higher ratings of ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]'', ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'', and ''[[Nightline (U.S. news program)|Nightline]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nReagan has worked in recent years as a magazine journalist, and has hosted talk shows on cable TV networks such as the [[Animal Planet]] network. In [[United Kingdom|Britain]], he is best known for having co-presented ''[[Record Breakers]]'' (based on ''[[The Guinness Book of Records]]'') for the [[BBC]]. Reagan presented a report from the United States each week.<ref>[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/571186/index.html Profile], screenonline.org.uk; accessed September 2, 2014.</ref>\n\nHe has served on the board of the [[Creative Coalition]], an organization founded in 1989 by a group that included [[Susan Sarandon]] and [[Christopher Reeve]], to politically mobilize entertainers and artists, generally for [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] rights, and causes such as arts advocacy and public education. From February to December 2005, Reagan co-hosted the talk show ''[[Connected: Coast to Coast]] with [[Monica Crowley]]'' on [[MSNBC]].<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|713985}}</ref>\n\nUntil its demise in 2010, [[Air America Media]] aired ''The Ron Reagan Show.'' The program made its debut on September 8, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reagan Joins Air America as Permanent Weeknight Host|work=Radio Online|date=September 4, 2008|url=http://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/$rol.exe/headline_id=n18357|accessdate=2013-11-27|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122220742/http://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/$rol.exe/headline_id=n18357|archivedate=2009-01-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, he published ''My Father at 100: A Memoir''.<ref name=\"Father at 100\">{{cite book | title=My Father at 100 | author=Ron Reagan |year=2011 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-670-02259-5 |oclc=646111792}}</ref> In interviews promoting the book, Reagan described noticing his father was having certain mental lapses which, in hindsight, caused the younger Reagan to speculate subsequently that his father may have already been in the early stages of [[Alzheimer's disease]] while still in office. This assertion was attacked by critics, including his brother, Michael Reagan. Ron Reagan subsequently clarified that he did not feel the lapses were evidence of \"dementia.\"<ref>''[[The Colbert Report]]'', January 18, 2011</ref>\n\nIn February of 1986, Reagan hosted ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.\n\n==Political activities==\nIn July 2004, Reagan spoke at the [[2004 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] about his support for lifting Bush's restrictions on federally funded [[embryonic stem cell research]], from which he expected a cure or new treatments for [[Alzheimer's disease]], of which his father had recently died. \"There are those who would stand in the way of this remarkable future, who would deny the federal funding so crucial to basic research. A few of these folks, needless to say, are just grinding a political axe and they should be ashamed of themselves,\" Ron Reagan said of the restrictions. \"We can choose between the future and the past, between reason and ignorance, between true compassion and mere ideology.\"<ref name=DNCSpeech>{{cite news|first=|last= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/27/politics/campaign/27TEXT-REAGAN.html|title=Ron Reagan's Speech to the Democratic National Convention|work=[[New York Times]]|date=Jul 27, 2004|accessdate=Sep 13, 2015}}</ref> Reagan's mother Nancy also supported this position.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/3700015.stm ''Nancy Reagan plea on stem cells'']. [[BBC News]]. May 10, 2004.</ref>\n\nIn September 2004, he told the ''[[Sunday Herald]]'' newspaper that the [[George W. Bush]] Administration had \"cheated to get into the White House. It's not something Americans ever want to think about their government. My sense of these people is that they don't have any respect for the public at large. They have a revolutionary mindset. I think they feel that anything they can do to prevail &mdash; lie, cheat, whatever &mdash; is justified by their revolutionary aims\" and that he feared Bush was \"hijacking\" his father's reputation.<ref>Johnston, Jenifer. [http://rense.com/general57/stop.htm ''Reagan Junior Warns Bush: 'Stop Hijacking My Father's Reputation'&#8288;'']. ''[[Sunday Herald]]''. September 26, 2004.</ref>\n\nReagan later wrote the essay \"The Case Against George W. Bush by Ron Reagan\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/cgi-bin/printtool/print.cgi?pages=5&filename=%2Ffeatures%2Farticles%2F2004%2F040729_mfe_reagan.html&x=38&y=16 |title=The Case Against George W. Bush |first=Ron |last=Reagan |work=[[Esquire Magazine|Esquire]] |year=2004 |accessdate=April 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040810032603/http://www.esquire.com/cgi-bin/printtool/print.cgi?pages=5&filename=%2Ffeatures%2Farticles%2F2004%2F040729_mfe_reagan.html&x=38&y=16 |archivedate=August 10, 2004 }}</ref> for ''[[Esquire Magazine|Esquire]]''. He voted for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] candidate [[John Kerry]] in the [[U.S. presidential election, 2004|2004 presidential election]]. Reagan endorsed then-senator [[Barack Obama]] of Illinois for president in the [[U.S. presidential election, 2008|2008 presidential election]].<ref>Reagan, Ron. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ron-reagan/making-it-official-i-endo_b_139932.html ''Making It Official: I Endorse Barack Obama'']. [[The Huffington Post]]. October 31, 2008.</ref> In November 2015, Reagan endorsed [[Vermont]] Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] for the Democratic Party nomination in the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Democratic Party primaries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/09/reagan-sons-interview-donald-trump-213149|title=GOP 2016: The Reagan Brothers on Donald Trump and the GOP|work=Politico Magazine|first=Elizabeth F.|last=Ralph|date=September 16, 2015|accessdate=November 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Reagan stated that his father would've opposed [[Donald Trump]], remarking to ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' that his \"father would have been ashamed of this Republican Party\" as well as \"been embarrassed and ashamed that a president of the United States was as incompetent and traitorous as the man occupying the White House now.\"<ref>https://www.thedailybeast.com/ron-reagan-says-his-father-ronald-reagan-would-not-want-republicans-to-vote-for-traitor-trump-in-2020</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRon Reagan lives in [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]].<ref name=\"thehill\"/> He married Doria Palmieri, a [[clinical psychology|clinical psychologist]], in 1980. She died in 2014 from [[neuromuscular disease]]. They had no children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/abcarian/la-me-ra-ron-reagan-endorses-atheism-20140530-column.html|title=Ron Reagan, not afraid to burn in hell, promotes atheism in TV spot|date=2014-05-30|accessdate=2014-06-12}}</ref> He married Federica Basagni in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/ron-reagan-says-his-father-ronald-reagan-would-not-want-republicans-to-vote-for-traitor-trump-in-2020 |title=Ron Reagan Says His Father, Ronald Reagan, Would Not Want Republicans to Vote for 'Traitor' Trump in 2020 |publisher=Thedailybeast.com |date=2020-01-17 |accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nReagan stated, in a 2004 ''[[New York Times]]'' interview, that he did not claim any religion, but that his sympathies were with [[Buddhism]] and his wife was a Buddhist.<ref name=\"SolomonInterview\">{{cite news|first=Deborah|last=Solomon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/27/magazine/27QUESTIONS.html?ex=1205812800&en=2cf65449d478f3c3&ei=5070|title=The Son Also Rises|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 27, 2004|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> In a June 23, 2004, interview on [[CNN]] show ''[[Larry King Live]]'', while discussing reasons why he would not run for political office, Ron Reagan stated \"I'm an [[atheism|atheist]]. ... I can't be elected to anything because polls all say that people won't elect an atheist.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview With Ron Reagan Jr.|work=Larry King Live (transcript)|publisher=CNN.com|date=June 23, 2004|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0406/23/lkl.00.html|accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, he was named to the [[Freedom From Religion Foundation]]'s Honorary Board of distinguished achievers.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://ffrf.org/news/releases/honorary-ffrf-board-announced/ |title= Honorary FFRF Board Announced |accessdate=2008-08-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101217052917/http://ffrf.org/news/releases/honorary-ffrf-board-announced/|archivedate=2010-12-17}}</ref> \nIn May 2014, Reagan appeared in an advertisement for broadcast on [[Comedy Central]] for the Freedom From Religion Foundation in which he declared himself \"an unabashed atheist,\" and one who is not afraid of \"burning\" in [[Hell]].<ref name=FFRF052014>{{cite web|title=First 'atheist ad' on 'Daily Show,' 'Colbert Report' features Ron Reagan|url=http://ffrf.org/news/news-releases/item/20732-first-%E2%80%98atheist-ad%E2%80%99-on-%E2%80%98daily-show%E2%80%99-%E2%80%98colbert-report%E2%80%99-features-ron-reagan|publisher=Freedom From Religion Foundation|date=May 20, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> The ad received renewed attention in October 2019 when it aired on CNN during the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums#Fourth debate (October 15, 2019)|fourth 2020 Democratic Presidential Debate]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A lot of people were Googling 'Ron Reagan' after his atheism ad aired|url=https://www.whas11.com/article/news/nation-world/ron-reagan-atheism-ad/507-90c1b182-e182-4060-9c5c-78433ad0c0cf|date=2019-10-15|accessdate=2019-10-16}}</ref> The ad was also run during the [[CNN]] Democratic debate in January 2020 and March 2020.\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|Journalism|Liberalism|Politics|Television|California|Chicago|United States|Religion}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2003/04/14/ron_reagan/ Reagan Blasts Bush (2003 interview)]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/15/us/2004-campaign-political-memo-reaganite-association-his-family-won-t-allow-it.html NYT: Reaganite by Association? His Family Won't Allow It]\n*[http://www.pr.com/article/1122 Ron Reagan] Interview on PR.com\n*{{C-SPAN|Ron Reagan}}\n*{{IMDb name|0713985|Ron Reagan}}\n\n{{Ronald Reagan}}\n{{Nancy Reagan}}\n{{MSNBC personalities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reagan, Ron}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American male ballet dancers]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:American television journalists]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Children of Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Reagan family|Ron]]\n[[Category:University of Southern California alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Writers from Seattle]]\n[[Category:MSNBC people]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:21st-century atheists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "107.77.229.177", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(It is accurate)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Reagan"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Herschel Schulman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Samuel Herschel Schulman\n| image              = Sammy-4.jpg\n| caption            = Sam Schulman at Virginia Holocaust Museum, 2003\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1928|7|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Terre Haute, Indiana]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2019|7|5|1928|7|8}}\n| death_place        = Richmond, Virginia, U.S.\n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| other_names        = Sam Schulman\n| occupation         = Seaman, Watchmaker/Jeweler\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = Crew member on the Aliya Bet ship 'Exodus 47'; early founder of Kibbutz Mishmar HaNegev; veteran of Israel's War of Independence\n| spouse             = \n| awards             = \n| website            = \n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Samuel Herschel Schulman''' (July 8, 1928 - July 5, 2019) was the last surviving American crew member of the celebrated ship ''[[Exodus 1947]],'' which attempted to bring thousands of Holocaust survivors from Europe to pre-state Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Born in Terre Haute, Indiana, to Jewish immigrants from Poland, he moved to Paris in 1932, surviving the [[Holocaust]] in hiding in central France. \n\nAfter the war, he was repatriated to the United States where he joined the [[Aliya Bet]], the clandestine immigration movement to bring Jews who survived the Holocaust in Europe to pre-state Israel, and then fought in Israel's [[War of Independence]]. \n\nSchulman returned to the United States in the 1950s and was drafted to the [[US Army]] during the [[Korean War]], serving two years training soldiers at [[Camp Edwards]] on Cape Cod, Massachusetts. After being released from the army, he went into jewelry business in New York City.\n\n== Early life ==\n\n=== Indiana ===\nSamuel Schulman was born in [[Terre Haute, Indiana|Terre Haute]], Indiana, on July 8, 1928. \n\nHis parents Hillel and Sarah Schulman (nee Sobkowska) immigrated to the United States from [[Warsaw]], Poland, in the 1920s. After his father died of appendicitis in 1932, he moved to Poland with his mother to be with her family. \n\nSarah Schulman remarried to an Orthodox rabbi, Moses Maidenbaum, and moved to [[Paris]], France, in 1933.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\n[[File:Teenager living in hiding in southern France.jpg|thumb|Sam Schulman as a teenager in Pionnat, France, 1944.]]\nIn May 1940, Germany invaded France and [[Paris in World War II|occupied Paris]] the following month. Sarah Schulman and her son had to register as Jews in order to obtain ration cards; she had to wear a Jewish star, but Sam Schulman, an American citizen, was exempt. Since Sarah Schulman was officially stateless, she could not return to the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1942, after the [[Gestapo]] conducted a round-up of Parisian Jews, Sam Schulman and his mother fled Paris. His step-father was on a business trip to the United States when the war broke out and could not return to France. \n\nSchulman and his mother were smuggled on a freight train to [[Limoges]], in the unoccupied zone, from where they continued to [[La Creuse]]. They remained in hiding in the small town of Pionnat, France, from 1942 to 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Features/Paris-to-Pionnat|title=Paris to Pionnat|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=December 10, 2007|website=Jerusalem Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> While Schulman and his mother survived the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], most of his family in Poland, including his grandmother, aunts and uncles, perished in [[Auschwitz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1946, Schulman and his mother were repatriated to United States through the [[Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society]] (HIAS).\n\n== Exodus and the Aliya Bet ==\n[[File:Dad Exodus47a.png|thumb|Sam Schulman aboard the SS Exodus, 1947.]]\n[[File:Exodus 1947 after British takeover.jpg|thumb|SS Exodus '47]]\nIn March 1947, Schulman was instructed by a contact in the [[Haganah]] in New York to go to [[Baltimore]], Maryland, where he thought he would board a ship as a passenger to [[British Mandate-Palestine|British-mandate Palestine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> When he got to the Baltimore Harbor on March 23, 1947, he learned that he was to become part of the [[Mossad LeAliyah Bet]] and serve as a crew member aboard the famed \"illegal\" refugee ship ''[[SS Exodus|Exodus 1947]]''. \n\nThe ''Exodus 1947'' left [[S\u00e8te]], France on July 11, 1947, with 4,515 Jewish refugees<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hochstein|first=Joseph|title=The Jews' Secret Fleet|publisher=Gefen|year=1987|isbn=965-229-023-8|location=Jerusalem|pages=}}</ref>. [[Ike Aronowicz]] was the ship's captain and the [[Haganah]] commander of the operation was [[Yossi Harel]]. The ship was manned by a crew of some 35 volunteers, mostly American Jews, including Samuel Schulman.\n\nSchulman also sailed on two other [[Aliyah Bet|Aliya Bet]] ships, the ''Pan Crescent'' and ''Pan York'', which left from the port of Burgas, Bulgaria, on December 27, 1947 with over 15,000 immigrants.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hochstein|first=Joseph|title=The Jews' Secret Fleet|publisher=Gefen|year=1987|isbn=965-229-023-8|location=Jerusalem|pages=}}</ref> Several days later they were stopped by British warships and forced to anchor at [[Famagusta]], Cyprus. \n\nAbout his experience on the ships, Schulman once said: <blockquote>''\u201cThe Exodus might have been the most famous of all the Aliya Bet ships, but the Pan ships brought the largest number of refugees from Europe at one time.\u201d'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.larchmontgazette.com/2003/features/20030802schulman.html|title=Larchmont Ex-Prisoner Returns to Famagusta|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=August 7, 2003|website=Larchmont Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> </blockquote>Schulman spent six weeks in a British internment camp on [[Cyprus]] before being smuggled out by the [[Haganah]] in January 1948 on the Jewish passenger liner the ''Kedmah'' under the alias of one of the immigrants approved by the monthly British quota to [[Mandatory Palestine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe ''Exodus'' was popularized in the 1958 bestseller of the same name by [[Leon Uris]], and later made into a Hollywood film based on the book starring [[Paul Newman]].\n\n== Israel ==\nArriving in the port of Haifa in January 1948, Schulman headed south to help settle Kibbutz [[Mishmar HaNegev]] with friends he knew from his youth movement days in France. \n\nHe would then fight in Israel\u2019s War of Independence, training seamen in navigation at a naval base in Haifa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1987, Schulman and other [[Aliyah Bet|Aliya Bet]] volunteers were honored by Israeli President [[Chaim Herzog]] for their contributions to the [[Israel|State of Israel]]. At this first reunion of the American volunteers in Jerusalem, Herzog said:<blockquote>''\"Out of six million American Jews, it was you who jumped into the breach.''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israel.org/MFA/MFA-Archive/1999/Pages/FOCUS%20on%20Israel-%20MACHAL%20-%20Overseas%20Volunteers.aspx|title=MACHAL - Overseas Volunteers|last=|first=|date=May 1999|website=Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>In a letter to mark the occasion, then-Minister of Defense, [[Yitzhak Rabin]], wrote:<blockquote>''\"Your participation in the struggle of the Jewish People to bring the Holocaust survivors to Eretz Israel will be inscribed in the history of the People of Israel as a bright chapter of volunteering spirit and as a meaningful contribution to the establishment of Israel.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.machal.org.il/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=585&Itemid=953&lang=en|title=Letter from Yitzhak Rabin to the Aliyah Bet Reunion in Israel|last=Rabin|first=Yitzhak|date=February 23, 1987|website=World Machal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>In November 2018, Schulman received a medal and certificate from Israeli Minister of Jerusalem and Heritage Affairs, [[Ze'ev Elkin]], for his contribution to bringing Jewish immigrants to [[pre-state Israel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.israelhayom.com/2018/11/29/aliyah-bet-illegal-immigrants-to-israel-to-receive-medal-of-honor/|title=Aliyah Bet 'illegal' immigrants to Israel to receive medal of honor|last=Lavie|first=Dan|date=November 29, 2018|website=Israel Hayom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== United States ==\nShortly after his return to the United States from Israel in 1949, Schulman was drafted to the [[Korean War]]. He spent two years training soldiers at [[Camp Edwards]] on Cape Cod, Massachusetts, rising to the rank of Sergeant First Class.\n\nAfter the war, Schulman studied at Brooklyn College and then at the Joseph Bulova School of Watchmaking in Queens, NY, on the [[GI Bill]]. He went on to set up a watchmaking business in the diamond exchange district on Canal Street and the Bowery in lower Manhattan where he worked for 40 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSam Schulman married Eileen Azif of Mt. Vernon, New York in 1964 and have two sons. His daughter-in-law is [https://embassies.gov.il/un/AboutTheEmbassy/Pages/Ambassador%20Noa%20Furman.aspx Noa Furman], Deputy Permanent Representative of Israel to the [[United Nations]]. \n\nA long-time resident of [[Larchmont, New York|Larchmont]], New York, Sam Schulman moved to [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], Virginia in 2014. He passed away a few days before his 91st birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n== References ==\n[[Category:The Holocaust]]\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Uris, Leon 1958, ''Exodus'' Doubleday Press, Chapter 27 specific to the Exodus true story.\n* Gruber, Ruth, 1999. ''Exodus 1947: the ship that launched a nation''. New York: Times Books. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/0-8129-3154-8|0-8129-3154-8]]. OCLC 4095423\n* Hochstein, Joseph M.; Murray Greenfield. ''The Jews' Secret Fleet''. Jerusalem: Gefen. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/965-229-023-8|965-229-023-8]]. OCLC 19030133\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.exodus1947.com/ Exodus1947.com] PBS Documentary Film focusing on the secret American involvement, narrated by Morley Safer\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q1mQuh9dy30 Sam Schulman - Oklahoma] Toldot Yisrael YouTube video\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mvKyVDfqFkM Sam Schulman video interview] Virginia Holocaust Museum\n*[https://collections.ushmm.org/search/?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=samuel+Schulman&search_field=all_fields Selected Sam Schulman documents and photos] US Holocaust Memorial Museum\n\n[[Category:World War II]]\n[[Category:Mandatory Palestine]]\n[[Category:Korean War]]\n[[Category:France]]\n[[Category:Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Samuel Herschel Schulman\n| image              = Sammy-4.jpg\n| caption            = Sam Schulman at Virginia Holocaust Museum, 2003\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1928|7|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Terre Haute, Indiana]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|mf=yes|2019|7|5|1928|7|8}}\n| death_place        = Richmond, Virginia, U.S.\n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| other_names        = Sam Schulman\n| occupation         = Seaman, Watchmaker/Jeweler\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = Crew member on the Aliya Bet ship 'Exodus 47'; early founder of Kibbutz Mishmar HaNegev; veteran of Israel's War of Independence\n| spouse             = \n| awards             = \n| website            = \n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Samuel Herschel Schulman''' (July 8, 1928 - July 5, 2019) was the last surviving American crew member of the celebrated ship ''[[Exodus 1947]],'' which attempted to bring thousands of Holocaust survivors from Europe to pre-state Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> Born in Terre Haute, Indiana, to Jewish immigrants from Poland, he moved to Paris in 1932, surviving the [[Holocaust]] in hiding in central France. \n\nAfter the war, he was repatriated to the United States where he joined the[[Aliya Bet]], the clandestine immigration movement to bring Jews who survived the Holocaust in Europe to pre-state Israel, and then fought in Israel's [[War of Independence]]. \n\nSchulman returned to the United States in the 1950s and was drafted to the [[US Army]] during the [[Korean War]], serving two years training soldiers at [[Camp Edwards]] on Cape Cod, Massachusetts. After being released from the army, he went into jewelry business in New York City.\n\n== Early life ==\n\n=== Indiana ===\nSamuel Schulman was born in [[Terre Haute, Indiana|Terre Haute]], Indiana, on July 8, 1928. \n\nHis parents Hillel and Sarah Schulman (nee Sobkowska) immigrated to the United States from [[Warsaw]], Poland, in the 1920s. After his father died of appendicitis in 1932, he moved to Poland with his mother to be with her family. \n\nSarah Schulman remarried to an Orthodox rabbi, Moses Maidenbaum, and moved to [[Paris]], France, in 1933.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\n[[File:Teenager living in hiding in southern France.jpg|thumb|Sam Schulman as a teenager in Pionnat, France, 1944.]]\nIn May 1940, Germany invaded France and [[Paris in World War II|occupied Paris]] the following month. Sarah Schulman and her son had to register as Jews in order to obtain ration cards; she had to wear a Jewish star, but Sam Schulman, an American citizen, was exempt. Since Sarah Schulman was officially stateless, she could not return to the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1942, after the [[Gestapo]] conducted a round-up of Parisian Jews, Sam Schulman and his mother fled Paris. His step-father was on a business trip to the United States when the war broke out and could not return to France. \n\nSchulman and his mother were smuggled on a freight train to [[Limoges]], in the unoccupied zone, from where they continued to [[La Creuse]]. They remained in hiding in the small town of Pionnat, France, from 1942 to 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Features/Paris-to-Pionnat|title=Paris to Pionnat|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=December 10, 2007|website=Jerusalem Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> While Schulman and his mother survived the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]], most of his family in Poland, including his grandmother, aunts and uncles, perished in [[Auschwitz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1946, Schulman and his mother were repatriated to United States through the [[Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society]] (HIAS).\n\n== Exodus and the Aliya Bet ==\n[[File:Dad Exodus47a.png|thumb|Sam Schulman aboard the SS Exodus, 1947.]]\n[[File:Exodus 1947 after British takeover.jpg|thumb|SS Exodus '47]]\nIn March 1947, Schulman was instructed by a contact in the [[Haganah]] in New York to go to [[Baltimore]], Maryland, where he thought he would board a ship as a passenger to [[British Mandate-Palestine|British-mandate Palestine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> When he got to the Baltimore Harbor on March 23, 1947, he learned that he was to become part of the [[Mossad LeAliyah Bet]] and serve as a crew member aboard the famed \"illegal\" refugee ship ''[[SS Exodus|Exodus 1947]]''. \n\nThe ''Exodus 1947'' left [[S\u00e8te]], France on July 11, 1947, with 4,515 Jewish refugees<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hochstein|first=Joseph|title=The Jews' Secret Fleet|publisher=Gefen|year=1987|isbn=965-229-023-8|location=Jerusalem|pages=}}</ref>. [[Ike Aronowicz]] was the ship's captain and the [[Haganah]] commander of the operation was [[Yossi Harel]]. The ship was manned by a crew of some 35 volunteers, mostly American Jews, including Samuel Schulman.\n\nSchulman also sailed on two other [[Aliyah Bet|Aliya Bet]] ships, the ''Pan Crescent'' and ''Pan York'', which left from the port of Burgas, Bulgaria, on December 27, 1947 with over 15,000 immigrants.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hochstein|first=Joseph|title=The Jews' Secret Fleet|publisher=Gefen|year=1987|isbn=965-229-023-8|location=Jerusalem|pages=}}</ref> Several days later they were stopped by British warships and forced to anchor at [[Famagusta]], Cyprus. \n\nAbout his experience on the ships, Schulman once said: <blockquote>''\u201cThe Exodus might have been the most famous of all the Aliya Bet ships, but the Pan ships brought the largest number of refugees from Europe at one time.\u201d'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.larchmontgazette.com/2003/features/20030802schulman.html|title=Larchmont Ex-Prisoner Returns to Famagusta|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=August 7, 2003|website=Larchmont Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> </blockquote>Schulman spent six weeks in a British internment camp on [[Cyprus]] before being smuggled out by the [[Haganah]] in January 1948 on the Jewish passenger liner the ''Kedmah'' under the alias of one of the immigrants approved by the monthly British quota to [[Mandatory Palestine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wertheimer.info/family/GRAMPS/Haapalah/ppl/a/6/be865525d2b5ece2a6a.html|title=Schulman, Samuel 'Sam' ben Tzvi (Hirsch)|last=|first=|date=September 2011|website=Haapalah / Aliyah Bet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe ''Exodus'' was popularized in the 1958 bestseller of the same name by [[Leon Uris]], and later made into a Hollywood film based on the book starring [[Paul Newman]].\n\n== Israel ==\nArriving in the port of Haifa in January 1948, Schulman headed south to help settle Kibbutz [[Mishmar HaNegev]] with friends he knew from his youth movement days in France. \n\nHe would then fight in Israel\u2019s War of Independence, training seamen in navigation at a naval base in Haifa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1987, Schulman and other [[Aliyah Bet|Aliya Bet]] volunteers were honored by Israeli President [[Chaim Herzog]] for their contributions to the [[Israel|State of Israel]]. At this first reunion of the American volunteers in Jerusalem, Herzog said:<blockquote>''\"Out of six million American Jews, it was you who jumped into the breach.''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.israel.org/MFA/MFA-Archive/1999/Pages/FOCUS%20on%20Israel-%20MACHAL%20-%20Overseas%20Volunteers.aspx|title=MACHAL - Overseas Volunteers|last=|first=|date=May 1999|website=Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>In a letter to mark the occasion, then-Minister of Defense, [[Yitzhak Rabin]], wrote:<blockquote>''\"Your participation in the struggle of the Jewish People to bring the Holocaust survivors to Eretz Israel will be inscribed in the history of the People of Israel as a bright chapter of volunteering spirit and as a meaningful contribution to the establishment of Israel.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.machal.org.il/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=585&Itemid=953&lang=en|title=Letter from Yitzhak Rabin to the Aliyah Bet Reunion in Israel|last=Rabin|first=Yitzhak|date=February 23, 1987|website=World Machal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>In November 2018, Schulman received a medal and certificate from Israeli Minister of Jerusalem and Heritage Affairs, [[Ze'ev Elkin]], for his contribution to bringing Jewish immigrants to [[pre-state Israel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.israelhayom.com/2018/11/29/aliyah-bet-illegal-immigrants-to-israel-to-receive-medal-of-honor/|title=Aliyah Bet 'illegal' immigrants to Israel to receive medal of honor|last=Lavie|first=Dan|date=November 29, 2018|website=Israel Hayom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== United States ==\nShortly after his return to the United States from Israel in 1949, Schulman was drafted to the [[Korean War]]. He spent two years training soldiers at [[Camp Edwards]] on Cape Cod, Massachusetts, rising to the rank of Sergeant First Class.\n\nAfter the war, Schulman studied at Brooklyn College and then at the Joseph Bulova School of Watchmaking in Queens, NY, on the [[GI Bill]]. He went on to set up a watchmaking business in the diamond exchange district on Canal Street and the Bowery in lower Manhattan where he worked for 40 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSam Schulman married Eileen Azif of Mt. Vernon, New York in 1964 and have two sons. His daughter-in-law is [https://embassies.gov.il/un/AboutTheEmbassy/Pages/Ambassador%20Noa%20Furman.aspx Noa Furman], Deputy Permanent Representative of Israel to the [[United Nations]]. \n\nA long-time resident of [[Larchmont, New York|Larchmont]], New York, Sam Schulman moved to [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], Virginia in 2014. He passed away a few days before his 91st birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/sam-schulman-last-surviving-us-crew-member-on-legendary-exodus-dies-at-91/|title=Sam Schulman, last surviving US crew member on legendary \u2018Exodus,\u2019 dies at 91|last=Schulman|first=Mark|date=July 5, 2019|website=Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n== References ==\n[[Category:The Holocaust]]\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Uris, Leon 1958, ''Exodus'' Doubleday Press, Chapter 27 specific to the Exodus true story.\n* Gruber, Ruth, 1999. ''Exodus 1947: the ship that launched a nation''. New York: Times Books. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/0-8129-3154-8|0-8129-3154-8]]. OCLC 4095423\n* Hochstein, Joseph M.; Murray Greenfield. ''The Jews' Secret Fleet''. Jerusalem: Gefen. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Special:BookSources/965-229-023-8|965-229-023-8]]. OCLC 19030133\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.exodus1947.com/ Exodus1947.com] PBS Documentary Film focusing on the secret American involvement, narrated by Morley Safer\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q1mQuh9dy30 Sam Schulman - Oklahoma] Toldot Yisrael YouTube video\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mvKyVDfqFkM Sam Schulman video interview] Virginia Holocaust Museum\n*[https://collections.ushmm.org/search/?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=samuel+Schulman&search_field=all_fields Selected Sam Schulman documents and photos] US Holocaust Memorial Museum\n\n[[Category:World War II]]\n[[Category:Mandatory Palestine]]\n[[Category:Korean War]]\n[[Category:France]]\n[[Category:Israel]]\n", "name_user": "Marknoa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed a space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Herschel_Schulman"}
{"title_page": "Amrita Singh", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{BLP sources|date=February 2013}}{{Unreliable sources|date=April 2016}}}}'''Amrita Singh''' (born 9 February 1958)<ref name=\"bollywood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iloveindia.com/bollywood/actresses/amrita-singh.html|title=Film Actress Amrita Singh&nbsp;\u2014 Bollywood Star Amrita Singh&nbsp;\u2014 Amrita Singh Biography&nbsp;\u2014 Amrita Singh Profile|publisher=|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> is an Indian actress. Through her films like ''[[Betaab]]'' and ''[[Mard]]'', she gained popularity and became a well known and popular actress in the 1980s. She took a break from acting in the early 1990s for a decade and returned to acting in 2002, occasionally playing supporting roles. She also made her debut on television in 2005.  Amrita keeps a low public profile and gives few interviews.\n\nShe is the daughter of [[Rukhsana Sultana|shahid kapoor]] who raised her as a single parent.\n\n== Early life ==\nShe was born in [[Hadali]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]] to a Muslim mother [[Rukhsana Sultana]]<ref name=\"TOI1\">{{cite web|last1=Varma|first1=Anuradha|title=In Bollywood, everyone's related!|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/In-Bollywood-everyones-related/articleshow/4654411.cms|website=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=21 April 2016|date=14 June 2009}}</ref> and a Sikh father, army officer Shivinder Singh Virk, from a feudal family.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rare Pictures & Interesting Facts about 80s B-town Sensation Amrita Singh|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/news-rec/ENT-CELE-amrita-singh-rare-pictures-interesting-facts-5244695-PHO.html?seq=2|website=Dailybhaskar.com|accessdate=21 April 2016|date=10 February 2016}}</ref> Her mother was a political associate of [[Sanjay Gandhi]] during the [[Indian Emergency]] in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Das|first1=Veena. (Editor)|last2=Tarlo|first2=Emma|title=Violence and subjectivity|date=2000|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=978-0-520-21608-2|page=266|edition= 9th printing.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=7KsEcQnb2VIC&oi=fnd&pg=PA242&dq=ruksana+sultana+sterilization+vasectomy&ots=GqZo1H38oz&sig=rpGbBhQYTlaxIXFBl_8gQT3k6p0#v=onepage&q=sultana&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Tarlo|first1=Emma|title=Unsettling memories : narratives of the emergency in Delhi|date=2001|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=978-0-520-23122-1|pages=38\u201339, 143|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=3IO1WB2H8UUC&oi=fnd&pg=PR5&dq=ruksana+sultana+sterilization+vasectomy&ots=LMdd4Ww_dG&sig=it0hAR3VF0L9lEo_w1aZ-Y6IVnY#v=onepage&q=sultana&f=false|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref><ref>Gwatkin, Davidson R. \"Political will and family planning: the implications of India's emergency experience.\" Population and Development Review (1979): 29-59.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=French|first1=Patrick|title=India : a portrait|date=2011|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-307-27243-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780307272430/page/43 43]|edition= 1st U.S.|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780307272430|url-access=registration|quote=rukhsana sultana .|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://satyagrah.scroll.in/article/12147/emergency-sterilization-rukhsana-sultana?|title=#1975Emergency \u0930\u0941\u0916\u0938\u093e\u0928\u093e \u0938\u0941\u0932\u094d\u0924\u093e\u0928\u093e : \u090f\u0915 \u092e\u0941\u0938\u094d\u0932\u093f\u092e  \u0938\u0941\u0902\u0926\u0930\u0940 \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0947 \u0926\u0947\u0916\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u0940 \u092e\u0941\u0938\u094d\u0932\u093f\u092e  \u092e\u0930\u094d\u0926\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0940 \u0930\u0942\u0939 \u0915\u093e\u0902\u092a \u091c\u093e\u0924\u0940 \u0925\u0940}}</ref> Through her paternal grandmother Mohinder Kaur, Amrita is the great-granddaughter of [[Sobha Singh (builder)|Sobha Singh]], one of the builders of New Delhi, and the great-niece of the late novelist [[Khushwant Singh]]. The actress [[Begum Para]] is her great-aunt and her husband was [[Nasir Khan (actor)|Nasir Khan]], who is the brother of [[Dilip Kumar]]. Actor [[Ayub Khan (actor)|Ayub Khan]] is her second cousin.<ref name=\"TOI1\" /> Singh was a childhood friend of [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]]. Their mothers often worked together in the Old Delhi area and Singh attended the same school as Khan's sister, Shahnaz.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chopra |first1=Anupama |title=King of Bollywood: Shah Rukh Khan and the Seductive World of Indian Cinema |date=2007 |publisher=Grand Central Publishing |edition= 1st}}</ref>\n\nSingh attended [[Modern School (New Delhi)|Modern School]] in New Delhi and is fluent in English, [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and [[Hindi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saifamrita.blogspot.co.uk/|title=Saif Ali Khan and Amrita Singh|author=rafflesia|publisher=|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 1983\u20131993 ===\nSingh made her [[Bollywood]] debut in 1983 with ''[[Betaab]]'', an immensely  successful film in which she was paired with [[Sunny Deol]]. This was quickly followed by a succession of hits, such as ''[[Sunny (1984 film)|Sunny]]'' in 1984, ''[[Mard (1985 film)|Mard]]'' (which was the biggest hit of that year) and ''[[Saaheb]]'' in 1985, ''[[Chameli Ki Shaadi]]'' and ''[[Naam (1986 film)|Naam]]'' in 1986 ,''[[Khudgarz]]'' in 1987, And ''[[Waaris (1988 film)|Waaris]]'' 1988. and  Singh made a successful pair in several films, not only with [[Sunny Deol]], [[Sanjay Dutt]], and [[Raj Babbar]], but also with [[Anil Kapoor]] and [[Amitabh Bachchan]], two leading actors of the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.desicommunityguide.com/gallery/AMRITHASINGH/profile.asp|title=Bollywood Actress: Amrita Singh's Biography|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506222937/http://www.desicommunityguide.com/gallery/AMRITHASINGH/profile.asp|archive-date=6 May 2008|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> As well as playing leading roles, she also played supporting negative roles in films such as ''[[Raju Ban Gaya Gentleman]]'' (1992) and ''[[Aaina (1993 film)|Aaina]]'' (1993). She also won the [[Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award]] for the latter. Amrita is a symbol of that era of Bollywood, when drama-romance-action charged Masala films were popular. She was famous icon of glossy make-up, long skirt and sleeveless gown. Her comic timings are still remembered. She decided to retire into family life and quit acting after her appearance in the 1993 film ''[[Rang (1993 film)|Rang]]''.\n\n=== 2002\u2013present ===\nSingh returned to acting in 2002 with the film ''[[23rd March 1931: Shaheed]]'', in which she played the mother of [[Bhagat Singh]] (played by [[Bobby Deol]]). She joined the television industry with [[Ekta Kapoor]]'s family drama ''[[Kavyanjali]]'', aired on [[Star Plus]] in 2005. Singh was seen in a negative role in the show, that soon gained immense popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kaneesha.com/amrita-singh|title=Amrita Singh|publisher=|accessdate=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505131053/http://www.kaneesha.com/amrita-singh|archive-date=5 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Later that year, she won acclaim for her performance in yet another negative role for the film ''[[Kalyug (2005 film)|Kalyug]]''. In 2007, Singh played the role of gangster [[Maya Dolas]]' mother, Ratnaprabha Dolas, in the [[Sanjay Gupta]] film ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]'', directed by Apoorva Lakhia. [[Vivek Oberoi]] played the role of Ma. Later on she appeared in the [[anthology film]] ''[[Dus Kahaniyaan]],'' where she appeared in the short story ''Poornmasi''.\n\nContinuing her acting journey, Singh played in the film ''[[Kajraare]]'' in 2010, and also appeared in ''[[Aurangzeb (film)|Aurangzeb]]'' under the [[Yash Raj Films]] banner, where she was paired with [[Jackie Shroff]] after almost two decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiawest.com/news/10571-arjun-kapoor-likely-to-team-up-with-yash-raj-films-again.html|title=Arjun Kapoor Likely to Team Up with Yash Raj Films Again|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222012153/http://www.indiawest.com/news/10571-arjun-kapoor-likely-to-team-up-with-yash-raj-films-again.html#YJFxpyQKXwtHO2zB.99|archive-date=22 February 2014|publisher=PTI|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> In 2014, she was seen in the film ''[[2 States (2014 film)|2 States]]'', produced by [[Dharma Productions]], portraying the role of co-actor [[Arjun Kapoor]]'s mother. The film released on 18 April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=2 States: Amrita Singh to play Arjun Kapoor's punjabi mother with an expert polish the role seemed totally typical or original in tone. On the other hand, Revati of south-indian films, as Alia's mother gave a skilled acting performance that was a pleasure for viewers.Also the unmatched relation with Ronit Roy's character was a strong feeling scene for viewers. Amrita was fabulous in 2 States. |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news-interviews/2-States-Amrita-Singh-to-play-Arjun-Kapoors-mother/articleshow/17950738.cms|work=the times of india|accessdate=18 March 2014}}</ref> In 2016, she appeared in ''[[Flying Jat]]'' playing [[Tiger Shroff]]'s mother and recently in 2017 she appeared in the acclaimed drama ''[[Hindi Medium]]''. She played the Principal's role for a glance. She was recently seen  in Sujoy Ghosh's ''[[Badla (2019 film)|Badla]]'', released on 8 March 2019. She played the role of Rani Kaur.\n\n== Personal life ==\nSingh married actor [[Saif Ali Khan]] in 1991. The couple married in an [[Nikah|Islamic wedding ceremony]].<ref name=\"tribune\">{{cite web|title=No one changes their religion in order to get married: Saif Ali Khan speaks about 'love jihad'|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/875213/no-one-changes-their-religion-in-order-to-get-married-saif-ali-khan-speaks-about-love-jihad/|website=[[The Express Tribune]]|accessdate=21 April 2016|date=24 April 2015}}</ref> Twelve years younger than her, Khan is the son of former Indian test cricket captain [[Mansoor Ali Khan Pataudi]], the ninth [[Nawab of Pataudi]] and actress [[Sharmila Tagore]]. Despite controversies, they remained married. She gave up acting after her marriage to Khan. After thirteen years of marriage, the couple divorced in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Iyer|first1=Meena|title=Bollywood has a low divorce rate|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Bollywood-has-a-low-divorce-rate/articleshow/45012318.cms|website=The Times of India|accessdate=21 April 2016|date=3 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nTheir daughter [[Sara Ali Khan]] was born on 12 August 1995 <ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/photo-features/sara-ali-khan-interesting-facts-about-the-star-kid/Sara-Ali-Khan-belongs-to-the-royal-family-of-Nawabs-of-Pataudi/photostory/63617193.cms</ref> and son Ibrahim Ali Khan on 5 March 2001. Sara graduated from Columbia University and their son Ibrahim Ali Khan is studying in England. Ibrahim was a child actor in the movie [[Tashan (film)|Tashan]]. Sara Ali Khan made her debut in the movie [[Kedarnath (film)|Kedarnath]] on 7 December 2018.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! class=\"unsortable\" | Other notes\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[Betaab]]'' || Roma (Dingy) ||\n|-\n| 1984 || ''[[Sunny (1984 film)|Sunny]]'' || Amrita ||\n|-\n| 1984 || ''[[Duniya (1984 film)|Duniya]]'' || Roma Verma ||\n|-\n| 1985 || ''[[Saaheb]]'' || Natasha 'Nikki' ||\n|-\n| 1985 || ''[[Mard (1985 film)|Mard]]'' || Ruby ||\n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Mera Dharam]]'' || Durga Thakur||\n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Chameli Ki Shaadi]]'' || Chameli ||\n|-\n| 1986 ||''[[Kala Dhanda Goray Log]]'' || Mrs. Ramola Gauri Shankar / Pooja ||\n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Karamdaata (1986 film)|Karamdaata]]'' || Pinky ||\